{"ts":"2026-06-27T03:03:12.912Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining the Application Scope**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the specifications. The core focus is establishing the shared app shell, meticulously excluding the landing page from any modifications. I've noted the responsive sidebar as a key component to integrate. The primary goal is to ensure consistency and a cohesive user experience across the client and admin portals.\n\n\n**Refining the Navigation Structure**\n\nI'm now diving into the navigation structure details. Specifically, I'm examining and refining the topbar and sidebar layouts. I'm focusing on the grouping of sidebar links on the desktop, and considering an improved mobile navigation structure. I'm looking into how `PrivateSidebar` currently renders and exploring ways to implement grouped navigation. The objective is grouped navigation and collapse behavior on desktop, bottom or drawer navigation on mobile, and clear active states. I am building a clear grouping mapping.\n\n\n**Mapping Sidebar Links**\n\nI've just finished mapping out the sidebar links for both the client and admin portals, creating separate arrays. I've defined labels, descriptions, and icons for each entry. The goal is now to integrate these new mappings into the navigation structure I previously refined. I am focusing on seamless display in the new layout.\n\n\n**Defining Dynamic Link Groups**\n\nI'm now determining dynamic link groupings based on functionality and access levels. I'm focusing on defining appropriate groups for these new portal links, such as \"Project Management\", \"System Administration\", and \"Financials\". I'm also planning the logic to ensure that only authorized links are visible to users. I'm aiming for flexibility and scalability.\n\n\n**Structuring Link Groups**\n\nI'm now focusing on implementing the logical link groupings I've defined, considering both client and admin portals. I'm leaning toward defining a helper function or map within `sidebar-topbar.tsx` or `routes-config.ts` to manage this structured data. I am thinking about how collapsed sidebar states will impact the visibility of the category titles and the user experience.\n\n\n**Evaluating Layout Enhancements**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on UI improvements, considering both desktop and mobile views. My plan is to optimize the sidebar and topbar design. I've noted that the `SecurePreviewNotice` is fixed at the top, which impacts layout, and I'm also planning to refine the `PrivateAppShell` and its handling of sidebar collapse states. I am focusing on the current layout behavior to identify potential for a premium design with efficient use of space. I'm focusing on the Workspace Switcher.\n\n\n**Implementing the Workspace Switcher**\n\nI'm now integrating a \"Workspace/Organization Switcher\" dropdown. I'm placing it near the GFF AI logo, displaying the active organization with a chevron for switching. The plan is to include a glowing green dot for the current workspace. I envision a dropdown list of available organizations. The sidebar groups are also being refined for a more premium look.\n\n\n**Designing Mobile Navigation**\n\nI'm now focusing on a highly responsive mobile navigation design. I've decided on a bottom navigation bar, visible only on smaller screens, that includes actions for Dashboard, Projects, AI Operations, Support/Docs, and a \"More\" option to open a drawer with full access. I'm prioritizing clear active states with blue highlights for the bottom navigation icons. The goal is rapid access to core functions on mobile, with a comprehensive drawer for full access.\n\n\n"}}
